-- Vacuous Truth
--
-- Classical: A -> B is true when A is false (paradox of material implication)
-- CredTT: When antecedent has c ~ 0, conditional is weakly constrained
--
-- Example: "If pigs fly, then 2+2=5"
-- Classical: TRUE (vacuously, since pigs don't fly)
-- CredTT: Conditional at very low credence (near-zero antecedent)

-- The classical paradox:
-- "If the moon is made of cheese, I am the Pope"
-- This is TRUE in classical logic! Because antecedent is false.

-- CredTT dissolves this paradox:
-- When antecedent credence -> 0, conditional becomes UNCONSTRAINED
-- Not "true" but "admissible with no information content"

-- Impossible antecedent at credence 0
postulate pigs_fly : pigs_can_fly @ 0

-- When antecedent is at credence 0:
-- P(B|A) is UNCONSTRAINED (see ex_falso)
-- So "pigs fly -> 2+2=5" is admissible but MEANINGLESS

-- The difference from classical:
-- Classical: vacuous truth is TRUE
-- CredTT: vacuous conditional is ADMISSIBLE but UNINFORMATIVE

-- Nearly-impossible antecedent at credence 0.001
postulate nearly_impossible : very_unlikely_A @ 1/1000

-- Conditional with near-zero antecedent:
-- P(B|A) is ALMOST unconstrained
-- Any P(B|A) is approximately compatible with the chain rule

-- This is the GRADED version:
-- c_A = 0: completely unconstrained (ex falso)
-- c_A = 0.001: almost unconstrained
-- c_A = 0.1: weakly constrained
-- c_A = 0.5: moderately constrained
-- c_A = 1: fully constrained

-- Classical logic only sees endpoints: true or false
-- CredTT sees the entire spectrum

-- Why this matters for real reasoning:
-- "If the test returns positive, you have the disease"
-- If P(positive) = 0.001, this conditional is weakly constrained
-- The conditional might be "true" but carries little information
-- CredTT tracks this; classical logic doesn't
